INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` (`entity_type`, `bundle`, `deleted`, `entity_id`, `revision_id`, `language`, `delta`, `body_value`, `body_summary`, `body_format`) VALUES ('node','tip',0,2,2,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It is important to encourage students to learn from each bug or mistake instead of letting them get discouraged.</li>\r\n<li>This encouragement is especially necessary for girls because they\'re more likely to drop out of tech coursework because they\'re afraid they won\'t succeed as opposed to actually failing academic work.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,4,4,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Emphasize how careers in STEM fields can hugely impact society for more socially-minded students.</li>\r\n<li>There are projected to be 1.4 million job openings in computer science by 2020, and the number of women in the field is dropping. Without these women, we won’t be able to fill all these jobs!</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,5,5,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Showing students proof that others have succeeded in the industry helps them to believe they can succeed.</li>\r\n<li>Being exposed to a wide variety of careers in CS will help students find their niche and emphasize how applicable CS skills are to the elusive “real world.”</li>\r\n<li>Girls are often apprehensive of being the only girl in the room, but interacting with women mentors will make the tech industry seem like less of a “boys’ club.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,6,6,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This environment can be created by positive reinforcement and treating failures as learning experiences rather than a reason to give up.</li>\r\n<li>A positive environment encourages students to believe they can meet all the challenges they’ll face in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,7,7,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Women are huge consumers of technology, but they are underrepresented in its design.</li>\r\n<li>As a result, companies are seeking more diverse perspectives in design to become closer to their consumers and increase profits.</li>\r\n<li>Encourage productive collaboration by telling students that teams comprised of many gender identities are more creative and productive.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,8,8,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This is important encouragement for students who think of computer science as sitting at a computer all day.</li>\r\n<li>Provide experiences in industry to allow students to see firsthand all the different tasks that occur in a computer science job.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,9,9,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students to think carefully about their questions.</li>\r\n<li>It will also promote collaboration in a productive way as an important step in development.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,10,10,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help teachers to design course curriculum based on the abilities of the students, and to highlight the subjects that might be most difficult for various students.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,11,11,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These basic, intro-level programming exercises will serve as introductions to the concepts of computer science, and can be telling for the ways students will struggle later on in terms of thinking about computer science concepts.</li>\r\n<li>More information about LightBot is available at: http://light-bot.com/</li>\r\n<li>More information about Picobot is available at: http://nifty.stanford.edu/2010/dodds-picobot/</li>\r\n<li>More information about Manufactoria is available at: http://pleasingfungus.com/Manufactoria/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,12,12,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will let students see the kind of opportunities they can have if they continue their studies in university.</li>\r\n<li>Students will also be able to see the older students as role models, which can be especially important for students who are minorities in the field.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,13,13,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Going back to the problem-solving nature of computer science can help students to understand that programming is first and foremost a way of thinking.</li>\r\n<li>This will encourage students who may not consider careers in computer science to take a computer science course.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,14,14,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This helps students to think about how they use programming tools in their daily lives, and makes lessons in the classroom seem more relevant to them.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,15,15,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be a fun exercise for more creative students, and it also requires an in-depth understanding of concepts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,16,16,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This kind of content organization would allow students to logically build up knowledge.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,17,17,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A good way of doing this is to create a list of what you want your students to take away from the course, and then find an IDE that fits most of these.</li>\r\n<li>This will ensure that teaching isn’t hindered by issues with the development environment.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,18,18,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help build their confidence and show them various ways of problem solving the difficulties that come with writing code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,19,19,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This helps to keep the course focused, and prevents doing activities just because they’re “cool.”</li>\r\n<li>Clear goals will also help to keep all students on the same page with progression through the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,20,20,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will encourage incoming students, as they will have a greater connection to peers who have taken the course before.</li>\r\n<li>It will also give you the ability to see what struggles your students have had during the year and appreciate the various ways that they overcame these struggles.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,21,21,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A large variety of speakers can help students to find their niche in the field, and also to provide them with potential mentors for their future work in computer science.</li>\r\n<li>It also shows students that real people are involved in computer science!</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,24,24,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If an answer is incorrect, ask the student to explain why they think a certain approach is correct, in order to ascertain where the misunderstanding lies.</li>\r\n<li>By focusing explicitly on the incorrect step when explaining mistakes, rather than the whole process, your students will feel more confident in their abilities overall.</li>\r\n<li>Students will be left more confident in their abilities if only the incorrect step, and not the whole process, is targeted.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,25,25,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Such skills help retain concepts with wide applications.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,26,26,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The most influential role models are those that students can easily believe in and relate to.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,27,27,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This also ensures that there is a clear connection between what the students expect to learn and the course content.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,28,28,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The easiest resources to access independently are often quickly found through a search engine and are not password-protected.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,29,29,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students draft their own letters of recommendation in the beginning of the year using pre-written templates, e.g. “X created outstanding tests for his code, which I sometimes used to catch problems in other students’ code.” versus “X made clear that he considered testing a waste of time.” at the beginning of the year.</li>\r\n<li>Using this framework, students can reflect on what makes a positive letter of recommendation and, by extension, a good student.</li>\r\n<li>Remind students that they’re in charge of their own performance in class— letters of recommendation don’t just emerge from nowhere!</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,30,30,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Often, students will want to bypass proposals and design documents in favor of starting to code as quickly as possible.</li>\r\n<li>Focus on how much time can be saved by planning before coding.</li>\r\n<li>Remind students that in reviewing their ideas before implementing them, they may catch big issues and find more efficient ways to write code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,31,31,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This counters the approach many students take: reviewing code only after many changes have been made, which causes students to spend a lot of time fixing mistakes they’d made.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,32,32,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students may find it funny or helpful to think about the “Five Stages of Code Review” (based on Dr. Elisabith Kubler-Ross’ book “Five Stages of Grief” from her book <em>On Death and Dying</em>):\r\n<ul><li>Disbelief: \"How could someone find so much to complain about in my code?!\"</li>\r\n<li>Anger: \"How dare someone suggest that a hash-map of hash-maps isn\'t an efficient way of storing data?\"</li>\r\n<li>Bargaining: \"Maybe if I add the comments the reviewer requested in one file, I won\'t have to fix the tricky Unicode issues in another.\"</li>\r\n<li>Depression: \"There was so much wrong with my code.  How can I show my face to the person who reviewed my code?\"</li>\r\n<li>Acceptance: \"Wow, my code is a lot better due to the feedback.  This is a useful process, although I bet it\'s occasionally painful for everyone.\"</li></ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,33,33,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Share relevant jokes, anecdotes, or webcomics— these are often written by and for programmers, and can remind students that even as a professional, things like being reviewed are still stressful; sometimes humorously so!</li>\r\n<li>Tell personal anecdotes about programming debacles. These remind students that they’re not alone.</li>\r\n</il>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,34,34,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Use students’ names in class, rather than labels like “the girl with the red hair.”</li>\r\n<li>This makes it easier to interact will all students, rather than only the ones whose names you know.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,35,35,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can prevent the creation of an informal student hierarchy that puts students with CS experience at the top.</li>\r\n<li>By not labeling experienced students as “smarter,” inexperienced students may feel more comfortable speaking up in class.</li>\r\n<li>Remind students that there are many kinds of expertise, and that being \"smart\" is not limited to having programming experience, to foster a more inclusive learning environment.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,36,36,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This prevents students from feeling they’re not “smart” because they didn’t do well on a test they were told would be “a slam dunk.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,37,37,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Calling on all students equally will make everyone feel more comfortable asking and answering questions, even if they’re not completely confident with their answer.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,38,38,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This shows students that the most important part of their education is learning the concepts and how to think about problems.</li>\r\n<li>Not penalizing small bugs in programs helps students realize mistakes are okay and they don’t have to be perfect.</li>\r\n<li>“A learning environment should be a place where making a mistake is an acceptable action.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,39,39,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>To call on students equally, make sure not to favor students, and ensure that students who don’t talk much are heard.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,41,41,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students are told that their solution is just as valid as a solution created by an instructor, they will be more confident in their abilities.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,42,42,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For example, some students may need to understand how they can apply their knowledge before they learn the details.</li>\r\n<li>Make it clear to your students how they can apply the information you are giving them.</li>\r\n<li>Try different instruction methods to support these learning differences.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,44,44,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It is important that students have a chance to work with content before assigning homework that builds on that material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,45,45,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students often get stuck and cannot demonstrate understanding when trying to parse unfamiliar syntax.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,47,47,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When a course has clear prerequisites, you avoid devoting a lot of lecture time to teaching concepts students already know.</li>\r\n<li>It can be particularly difficult to match the pace of an intro course with the pace of the students when you have both students that are new to Computer Science and others that are already experienced.</li>\r\n<li>It can be helpful to split an intro course into two separate courses: one for students new to Computer Science and another for those that are experienced.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,48,48,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When certain assignments receive low scores across classes, it’s probably an indication that the assignment is ineffective.</li>\r\n<li>Incorporate a mechanism for identifying ineffective assignments to ensure meaningful coursework.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,49,49,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A lack of comfort with environments such as Unix can obstruct students\' focus on the learning objective.</li>\r\n<li>Video tutorials that familiarize students with environments can be an essential resource. Post these on your class website or YouTube channel.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,50,50,'und',0,'<ul><li>Useful tools that may not be explicitly part of the curriculum include:\r\n<ul><li>debugging</li>\r\n<li>language-specific syntax (Unix in particular)</li>\r\n<li>breaking down a problem into bite-size pieces</li>\r\n<li>how to use a coding environment like Eclipse</li></ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,51,51,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Ask students what components need to go in each part of a ‘for loop’ first, to help support them in writing well-developed ‘for loops.’</li>\r\n<li>Encourage students to write helper functions as opposed to lengthy, multi-purpose functions by limiting the number of lines a function can be.</li>\r\n<li>Explain that the process of breaking a problem into pieces is also helpful for solving problems in industry.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,52,52,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Explicitly write, cross out, and update variable-value pairs when tracing through code that iterates.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,53,53,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It can be helpful to draw an arrow from one diagram to the next to indicate where a function call was made and that control is being passed. After the call has completed, the arrow can be erased to indicate a return of control.</li>\r\n<li>This method can also be applied when teaching Assembly -- have the diagrams represent the different phases of the stack.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,54,54,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>More explicitly consider the following conversation metaphor: A primary function may ASK a secondary function a QUESTION by calling it. The secondary function RESPONDS by returning an answer.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,56,56,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If technical language is necessary, be sure to give sufficient definitions.</li>\r\n<li>Peer tutors can be helpful for reiterating information to students in a more colloquial manner, like reinforcing technical definitions.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,59,59,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students think about the goal at the highest level and work their way back to the code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,60,60,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Help students see writing code as a way to translate their ideas to the computer.</li>\r\n<li>Students often get stuck developing a solution in terms of the syntax of a specific programming language.</li>\r\n<li>Consider requiring that your students turn in a pseudocode solution to an assignment before allowing them to begin programming.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,61,61,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These interests might include designing and building games.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,62,62,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be used to help with teaching algorithms, data structures, and other more complex concepts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,64,64,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This is an essential programming skill that they can apply to almost any problem they have to solve in CS.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,66,66,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Collaborate with coworkers to make use of everyone’s strengths.</li>\r\n<li>It is often helpful to see other teachers’ real lessons, from online video libraries or your colleagues’ lectures, to improve your own lesson planning.</li>\r\n<li>New pedagogical research can often be incorporated into your classroom technique.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,67,67,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This approach to course design incentivizes students to endure more difficult assignments on which they might otherwise give up.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,68,68,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule time to meet with students and discuss their performance, their time management strategies, and how they can improve.</li>\r\n<li>Write personalized notes to each student. 2-3 sentences can go a long way.</li>\r\n<li>If you find the note creation process too time consuming, consider writing a script that personalizes notes or emails based on parameters such as scores and class participation.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,69,69,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Sharing your own struggles can also help you connect with your students.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,70,70,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Given the easy access to Computer Science resources outside of the classroom, students may feel intimidated by those that are already knowledgeable of course content.</li>\r\n<li>Tell students that learning is a process, and even though people may be at different stages in the process, everyone is going in the same direction.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,72,72,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If you have access to iClickers, consider polling your students during class to gauge how far into an assignment they are.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,73,73,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Tell students that reading an assignment and making mental or physical notes counts as starting it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,75,75,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Discuss what went wrong and how to improve.</li>\r\n<li>Encourage students to not be content until they fully understand a topic.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,76,76,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Encourage students to take pride in gaining new understanding.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,78,78,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Seeing peers teaching gives students confidence that they, too, can understand the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,80,80,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://www.problets.org/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,81,81,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://codingbat.com/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,82,82,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://byob.berkeley.edu/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,83,83,'und',0,'Find the resource at http://practiceit.cs.washington.edu/practiceit/','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,84,84,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For instance, assign students to roles where other students feel comfortable asking them for help, such as group leaders.</li>\r\n<li>This reiterates the confidence you have in your students.</li>\r\n<li>In addition, students may learn better from peers.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,85,85,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This also demonstrates to students that you are equally confident in all their abilities.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,86,86,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Common issues to look out for include leadership attempts. For instance, boys may be seen as more “appropriate” leaders than girls.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,87,87,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The goals of any task, as explained by the teacher, guide the student towards what is important.</li>\r\n<li>Without such guidance, it is easy for students to get confused about what the point of a particular exercise was.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,88,88,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>In particular, one-on-one conversations can encourage them to open up and share concerns.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,89,89,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students create clones with another block, like “when spacebar pressed”, these clones will also create clones when the spacebar is pressed, so the total number of clones increases by a factor of 2 every time the spacebar is pressed. This is generally unwanted behavior.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,90,90,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Create Your Own Block can be used to store useful things like helper functions. This can make it easier to teach students how to break up large problems in Scratch and can thus help with debugging. Students can easily test which of their smaller functions is not working properly.</li>\r\n<li>There are also many scripts that students will use often (like a script that clears the stage and moves the sprite to center) that can be made into a single procedure with Create Your Own Block. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,91,91,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>In a top-down process, students look at the larger problem and then divide the problem into smaller pieces with a logical structure. (Decomposing a problem.)</li>\r\n<li>Alternatively, a bottom-up process asks students to combine smaller pieces to solve the larger problem. (Composing a solution from already existing pieces.)</li>\r\n<li>Create Your Own Block provides a way for students to define simple procedures and helper functions that can then be called to create more complex procedures. For example, students can make a block that draws a petal/leaf which they can then use in a block that draws an entire flower.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,92,92,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Scope works a little differently in Scratch than in other languages. A variable that is “For this sprite only” can still be read by other sprites, but only the sprite that owns it can write to it. Variables that exist “For all sprites” act like global variables. This can help students when deciding what scope of variables to use for different tasks.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,93,93,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will show students that they can always learn something new, so they shouldn’t expect to learn everything now.</li>\r\n<li>This will also help students figure out good ways of learning new things by watching you learn.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,94,94,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help them not feel discouraged if they get stuck, or a problem takes them a long time to figure out.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,95,95,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If a strategy is successful for one student, it’s likely it can be successful for other students.</li>\r\n<li>Take the opportunity to learn from your students to improve how you teach the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,96,96,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help you keep track of how students are progressing, as well as see what concepts are more difficult and might require more time, and which are easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,97,97,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be accomplished in a variety of ways, such as letting the student come up with the main idea, and then come up with an action plan for the project.</li>\r\n<li>This will help both of you expand your knowledge of the project.</li>\r\n<li>You can also use this as an opportunity to help students start the project, which can be one of the hardest parts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,98,98,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Questions can help you determine what students are having trouble with, as well as help push them in the right direction.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,99,99,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will allow your students to follow the same procedure when they work alone on assignments.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,100,100,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students see exactly where their code is going wrong, so they know what part of their code needs to be fixed.</li>\r\n<li>This can also help students understand how their programs run, so in the future debugging will be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,101,101,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These should include interesting challenges you know at least one way to solve.</li>\r\n<li>You could also motivate your students to try to find other solutions to the challenges.</li>\r\n<li>For example, writing a procedure that draws your initials, or asks knock-knock jokes.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,102,102,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students think about the concepts in another way, which can help with their understanding.</li>\r\n<li>For example, have your students think about information stored on the disk as a notebook they keep adding information to.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,103,103,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students will realize that everyone gets bugs, even people with coding experience.</li>\r\n<li>Use this opportunity to emphasize that finding and getting rid of bugs is a learning experience, so next time it’ll be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,104,104,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>“If you can describe it, you can solve it!”</li>\r\n<li>If students can describe their bugs, they know exactly what it’s doing, so they can figure out how to get rid of it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,105,105,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students compare what their code is doing and what it’s supposed to be doing, they can determine where the error is.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,106,106,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If the code is in smaller pieces, it’s easier to pinpoint what parts aren’t working and focus on them rather than the entire program.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,107,107,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can also help students determine what bugs they tend to make so they can avoid making the same bugs in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,108,108,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>“A rested, relaxed mind may just get the solution without trying!”</li>\r\n<li>Just like while sleeping, their brain will keep thinking about the problem during the break, so when they come back to working it will be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,109,109,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students check the obvious and talk through the bug before getting involved.</li>\r\n<li>This will help students hone their debugging technique and help them debug on their own in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,111,111,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Examples of such activities include:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>debugging</li>\r\n<li>analyzing raw code or output</li>\r\n<li>reflecting on intuition vs. reality</li>\r\n<li>writing a task using different methods</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,112,112,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Consider roles for:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Keeping the group focused</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring everyone contributes and is heard</li>\r\n<li>Mediating between the group and those outside of it (including the teacher and the class)</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring that individual responses are consistent with group consensus</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring that the group’s work meets the expectations and is easy to understand</li>\r\n<li>Discussing with the group how the workflow could be improved</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,115,115,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can work well if students are creating games or websites.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,116,116,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Good examples can show students valuable ways to approach problems, and walk them through the steps.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,117,117,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can help students with their problem-solving skills and determining how to write code that is compatible on many systems.</li>\r\n<li>Especially with HTML5, students can find pieces that aren’t compatible with all browsers.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html');
